Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is PCA?
AI Response

Principal Component Analysis reduces dimensionality by transforming data to axes of greatest variance. It
reduces noise, speeds up training, and helps visualize high-dimensional data.

Example 1.2

User

What is the ROC curve?
AI Response

The ROC curve plots true positive rate vs false positive rate at various thresholds. AUC (Area Under Curve)
summarizes performance—a perfect model has AUC = 1.0.

Example 1.3

User

What is BERT?
AI Response

BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) is a pre-trained transformer model that
understands context from both directions in a sentence, excelling at NLP classification tasks.

Example 1.4

User

What is precision vs recall?
AI Response

Precision is correct positive predictions / all positive predictions. Recall is correct positive predictions / all
actual positives. F1 score harmonically balances both.

Example 1.5

User

What is a neural network?
AI Response

A neural network is a series of algorithms modeled after the human brain, consisting of input, hidden, and
output layers, with weights adjusted during training to minimize prediction error.

Example 1.6

User

What is regularization?
AI Response

Regularization adds a penalty to the loss function to discourage model complexity. L1 promotes sparsity; L2
penalizes large weights. Both reduce overfitting.

Example 1.7

User

What is RLHF?
AI Response



Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback trains a reward model on human preference data, then uses
RL (PPO) to fine-tune an LLM to produce outputs humans prefer.

Example 1.8

User

What is tokenization in NLP?
AI Response

Tokenization splits text into smaller units (tokens) such as words, subwords, or characters. Subword
tokenization (BPE, WordPiece) balances vocabulary size with handling of rare words.

Example 1.9

User

What is backpropagation?
AI Response

Backpropagation computes gradients of the loss with respect to each weight by applying the chain rule
backwards through the network, enabling weight updates via gradient descent.

Example 1.10

User

What is an autoencoder?
AI Response

An autoencoder learns a compressed (latent) representation of input data through an encoder, then
reconstructs it with a decoder. Used for dimensionality reduction, denoising, and anomaly detection.



